snippet.textDisplay: Why would you plug a vacuum that is probably going 1,000-1,500 watts into a a plug that clearly said 400 watts on it? You don’t look for voltage because all standard household voltage ranges 110-120volt and or 220-240 if you running your oven or dryer but no car is going to have 220. So when you want to know if the inverter will handle it you look at watts and most inverters read peak watts not running watts so a 400 watt plug would most likely only be good for under a 200 watt load with peaks or spikes of up to 400. A vacuum using a motor will tend to have a high start up power requirement and ease back some when at running speeds until it’s put under load again. Anyway just some info to help. FYI most those car inverters are small and are meant to power a laptop or small tv for camping and what not but ac motors are to much for them also if the vacuum or whatever you plug in does not have its wattage then just take the volts times the amps and you get the watts i.e a 120volt 10amp ship vac is 1,200 watts.
